<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">The highest-leverage teacher move of the unit. Watch a complete Brief built live.</p>
  <p>Mr. Ignash demos a complete <a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Chennai Climate Brief</a> on a familiar challenge — outdoor workers and heat mortality (the <strong>Heat Mortality worked example</strong>, printed + in Classroom). The point: make the policy-brief voice visible. Image-led opening (a specific worker's death, not a generic statistic). Physics embedded in human context (wet-bulb temperature explained as the physiological limit, not as abstract climate science). Three scenarios <em>differentiated</em> (status quo vs. increased monsoon variability vs. sea-level rise — each with distinct consequences for outdoor workers). Equity-aware recommendations (who acts, what it costs, who benefits, who bears burden). Honest AI Doc (the AI made up a death-count figure; the student verified against TN Public Health Department data and cited the discrepancy).</p>
  <p>Then 30 minutes of work time on YOUR Brief, with the <a href="/ai-partners/policy-aide/">Policy Aide</a> available for voice-coaching. Then 20 minutes of structured peer feedback in pairs, focused on the three rubric gates: <strong>policy voice</strong> (not academic-essay), <strong>audience awareness</strong> (Greater Chennai Corporation officials, not students), <strong>recommendation concreteness</strong> (no "raise awareness").</p>
</section>

